lectualist conception of the ethical virtues. Aristotle values these traits because, by subordinating emotion to reason, they enhance our ability to lead a life devoted to philosophy or politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAlbertus Magnus.  aAquinas.  aAsmis, Elizabeth.  aDarwin, Charles.  aDirlmeier, Franz.  aDuring, Ingemar.  aEudoxus.  aEuripides.  aEustratius.  aFreeland, Cynthia.  aGould, Stephen Jay.  aIsaeus.  aKenny, Anthony.  aKeyt, David.  aPericles.  aSolon.  aWilkes, Kathleen.  aWilliams, Bernard.  aWoods, Michael.  aamusement.  aconflict among persons.  acourage.  acrafts.  aemotion.  afunction.  agenerosity.  ahierarchy: of ends.  ahonor.  ahuman good.  aimprecision of practical thought.  ainclusivism.  ainequality.  aintrinsic goodness.  ajustice.  amagnanimity.  amagnificence.  amethodology.  amisfortune.  aostracism.  aperfect ends.  aphilosophia.  apleasure.  apractical reason.  apractical wisdom.  aself-love.  aself-sufficiency.  aslavery.  atemperance.  atheoretical reason.  aultimate end.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691225128zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691225128423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691225128.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EB